A debounce function delays the execution of a given function until a specified time has passed since its last invocation, useful for preventing excessive function calls during rapid user interactions.

```javascript
function debounce(func, delay) {
  let timeout;
  return function() {
    const ctx = this;
    const args = arguments;
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(function() {
      func.apply(ctx, args);
    }, delay);
  };
}

// Example usage
const debouncedFunction = debounce(function() {
  console.log("Debounced function called!");
}, 500);

// Call the debounced function multiple times
debouncedFunction();
debouncedFunction();
debouncedFunction();

// Output: "Debounced function called!" will only be logged once, 500ms after the last call
```

In this example, `debouncedFunction` will only be executed once, 500ms after the last time it was called. If it's called multiple times within that 500ms window, the previous pending execution will be cancelled and the timer will reset.
